    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Borders of particularly rich embroidery or woven designs in gold thread and colored silk, often embellished with jewels or beads, used as ornamental bands on clothing, such as on royal or ecclesiastical vestments. Term refers to the Phrygians, who were noted for their skill in embroidering with gold.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000008131/Century Dictionary and Cyclopedia (1906-1909)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000079245/Catholic Encyclopedia [online] (2003-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000052994/Higgens, Cloth of Gold: History of Metallised Textiles (1993)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Randen met bijzonder rijk borduurwerk of met gouddraad of gekleurd zijde geweven patronen, vaak verfraaid met juwelen of kralen. Gebruikt als ornamentele banden op kleren, zoals koninklijke of religieuze gewaden. De term verwijst naar de Frygiërs, die bekendstonden om hun grote vaardigheden in het borduren met goud.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Borte mit besonders prächtigen Stickereien oder aus gewebten Stoffen mit Goldfaden und aus gefärbter Seide, häufig mit Edelsteinen oder Glasperlen verziert; wird als ornamentaler Streifen für Kleidung verwendet, wie etwa an Königs- oder Kirchengewändern. Die Bezeichnung verweist auf die Phryger, die für ihre Goldstickereien bekannt waren.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>German</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000232/IfM-SMB-PK</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000122134/IfM Berlin</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>以金線及色絲織成，式樣格外華麗的刺繡或織品滾邊，多半鑲有寶石或琉璃珠子，用以為皇室或教會禮服等服裝之飾帶。本詞彙源於佛里幾亞人，他們以黃金刺繡技術聞名。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
